Taiwan is becoming a bigger issue between the world's two biggest superpowers. Taipei — a U.S. ally — and Beijing have avoided war for more than seven decades, but that balance is getting harder to maintain as China becomes more assertive in its desire for reunification.

Watch the full video at the link in bio to understand why analysts say Taiwan's status is "the most likely issue to draw China and the U.S. into a direct military conflict."

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 20, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, outdoors and text.

node.text:
Someday, the post-pandemic equities rally is going to end. When it does it will take a lot of newly christened stock bulls with it.

Retail investors' refusal to bend has been the signature fact of the stock market for at least 12 months. In 2021 alone, their appetite for dip-buying has put a floor under four other selloffs that look much like the one that sheared almost 3% off the S&P 500 Index since Thursday.
 
Whether their devotion is enough to turn the tide again is the biggest question in markets right now. Read more at the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 19, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, outdoors and text that says 'Wall Streetis paying young bankers more than ever to cloak a brutal work life Bloomberg Wealth'.

node.text:
All around Wall Street, junior bankers are quitting or face burnout. Banks are trying to turn the tide with raises, bonuses, vacations and even free Pelotons, all representing a silent plea: Please don’t quit.

All that means it’s never been more lucrative to be a young banker in the U.S. The problem, though, is that it’s also never been more lucrative for aspirants to work outside the gilded world of finance — and bank analysts’ grueling workloads have remained, and in some cases gotten worse. Read more at the link in bio.

📷: Spencer Platt/Getty Images

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 19, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and text that says 'Wall Street's new fear is that the economy has already peaked LOUISVUTTION NA ZAR Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Investment strategists are starting to consider a new bearish scenario: the economy has already hit its peak.

Investors had earlier delighted in the prospect of a strong worldwide economic rebound fueled by easy money and vaccine rollouts. But with the ferocious spread of the delta variant and central banks already talking about tighter monetary policy to bring inflation under control, there’s a sense of worry that financial markets have become too optimistic. 

With global equities teetering at all-time highs, there’s no room for error. Read more at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 19, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Plan Crypto traders loved big leveraged bets. Then came an inexplicable crash. Bloomberg'.

node.text:
On the day of one of the cryptocurrency market’s worst routs, Alex Holland woke up to a wave of messages from friends and family. They knew he had made a big wager recently that prices would fall.

But when he went to check his account on online exchange Binance, he saw that the value of his leveraged bet against Ethereum was sinking rather than reaping huge gains. “I thought it was just a bug and they’d be fixing it,” he says.

By the end of May 19, Ethereum would plummet roughly 20% and Holland’s so-called down token tumbled about 85%. The value was so low it appeared as zero on price charts.

Leveraged tokens are pitched by crypto exchanges as an easy way for amateurs to make outsized bets. In a way, it’s a cautionary tale as old as Wall Street — retail speculators burned by byzantine derivatives — amplified by a lack of regulation, creaky market plumbing, and the extreme volatility of the $1.3 trillion crypto world. Find out more at the link in bio.

📷: A man attends the Bitcoin 2021 Convention in Miami, Florida. By Marco Bello/AFP via Getty Images

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 19, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, standing, outdoors and text.

node.text:
“Space, the final frontier,” Jeff Bezos said in his high school valedictorian speech. “Meet me there.” On Tuesday, the billionaire will at last get his chance.

The New Shepard spacecraft is scheduled to lift vertically off the desert floor at his ranch in West Texas, travel 62 miles overhead and then detach a crew capsule in which Bezos, his brother, and two passengers will enjoy about three minutes of weightlessness.

A successful launch will represent a delayed triumph of sorts for Bezos and his private space company, Blue Origin. Over the years, the New Shepard program has suffered setbacks and required such significant capital that insiders doubt it will ever be profitable.

But for Amazon’s founder, who has harbored a lifelong dream of opening the space frontier, that may no longer be the goal. Find out more at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 19, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Bored ex-Lehman trader builds a $6.7 billion fortune withahotapp hot with a Bloomberg Wealth'.

node.text:
Nikolay Storonsky spent his 20s at Lehman Brothers and Credit Suisse before deciding to quit and set up on his own.
 
The 36-year-old, who's originally from Russia, says career malaise was a factor. "As a banker I'd already reached the maximum," he says. "It became very boring."

Storonsky co-founded Revolut, which provides online financial services. Last week, it raised $800 million at a $33 billion valuation; at that level, his stake is worth $6.7 billion, according to the Bloomberg Billionaires Index.

But while it's expanding rapidly, the company is also drawing regulatory scrutiny. Read the full story at the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business in London, United Kingdom. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Soaring Covid cases and Boris Johnson's isolation overshadow "Freedom Day" 이生土 DROIT 。၁ Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Boris Johnson's plan to get the U.K. back to normal is in disarray.
 
On the day of England’s big reopening, new cases have risen to the most in the world. Health Secretary Sajid Javid has tested positive for Covid-19, and both the prime minister and Chancellor Rishi Sunak have been forced to self-isolate — after a public outcry over a perceived attempt to dodge rules that have caused disruption to people and businesses across the country.

Legal curbs are lifting and London is, in theory, open again. But this is no end-of-pandemic celebration. Tap the link in our bio for what awaits City workers on “Freedom Day.”

📷: Daniel Leal-Olivas-WPA Pool/Getty Images

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 18, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, people standing, ocean, sky and text that says 'Grandparents arents aren't always happy moving closer to family BloombergOpinion'.

node.text:
After a difficult year when many grandparents didn't see their grandchildren, some are considering moving closer to family.

But should the emotional pull of being near loved ones always win out over the practical considerations of such a big decision?

@bloombergopinion's Teresa Ghilarducci writes: "Think about whether where they live is where you ultimately want to be, apart from your grandchildren. Does the area promote your health, your friendships and let you pursue your interests?"

Tap the link in our bio to read more about why retirees aren't always happy relocating closer to family.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 18, 2021. May be an image of 2 people and text that says 'Brazil's billionaire Batista brothers arut jail are out and even richer Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Just under four years ago, brothers Joesley and Wesley Batista were in Brazilian prison cells with concrete bunk beds, their multibillion-dollar meat empire near collapse in one of the world’s biggest corporate corruption scandals.

In 2017, they turned on a network of politicians they’d spent years cultivating through legal and off-the-books donations. What followed was a scandal so widespread that it led to “Joesley Day,” one of the worst market routs in Brazil’s history.

Today, they’re not only free men but their company, JBS, is worth three times what it was then, operates in 20 countries and controls a quarter of U.S. beef processing. The brothers, worth $5.8 billion, hold stakes in companies with $28 billion in assets. Find out more about their revival at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on July 18, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'The five biggest challenges facing Angela Merkel's successor Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Even after her remarkable run as Germany’s first female chancellor, Angela Merkel has unfinished business.
 
The Germany that Merkel created in her 15 years in power is running out of steam. For all her virtues as a crisis fighter, problems like the future of the car industry and the economic threat from China present a daunting challenge for her successor.

Her replacement will take the reins in a matter of weeks. Tap the link in our bio for more on the five key items on their to-do list.

📷: Jochen Zick - Pool / Getty Images
